"greater-kudu":{n:"Greater Kudu",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Large",cl:"Grey-Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Greater_kudu",d:"Males carry spectacular spiral horns up to 1.8 metres long. The kudu's silhouette forms the SANParks logo. They have 6-10 white body stripes and large ears. Excellent jumpers, easily clearing 2.5 metre fences despite their size.",w:"120-315 kg",l:"1.9-2.5 m",life:"7-23 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Browser â€” leaves, herbs, fruit",cs:"Least Concern"},
"eland":{n:"Eland",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Very Large",cl:"Tawny",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Common_eland",d:"World's largest antelope with bulls up to 900 kg. Despite massive size, they can jump 2+ metres from standing. A clicking sound when walking comes from tendons slipping over leg bones. Both sexes carry spiralling horns.",w:"400-900 kg",l:"2-3.4 m",life:"15-20 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Browser/Grazer",cs:"Least Concern"},
"red-hartebeest":{n:"Red Hartebeest",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Large",cl:"Reddish Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Red_hartebeest",d:"Distinguished by elongated faces and uniquely shaped horns. One of the fastest antelope at 70 km/h. Prefer open grasslands and often graze alongside zebras. Males use termite mounds as lookout posts.",w:"120-200 kg",l:"1.5-2.5 m",life:"11-20 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Grazer â€” grasses",cs:"Least Concern"},
"springbok":{n:"Springbok",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Medium",cl:"Tawny & White",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Springbok",d:"South Africa's national animal, famous for 'pronking' â€” stiff-legged jumps up to 2 metres high. A back fold of white-haired skin opens during pronking, releasing a sweet scent. Can reach 88 km/h.",w:"30-44 kg",l:"1.2-1.5 m",life:"7-9 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Mixed feeder",cs:"Least Concern"},
"gemsbok":{n:"Gemsbok",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Large",cl:"Grey & Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Gemsbok",d:"Powerful, horse-like antelope with dramatic black and white facial markings and horns up to 1.2 m. Both sexes carry horns. Can survive without drinking water. Horns are so sharp they've been known to kill lions.",w:"100-240 kg",l:"1.5-2.3 m",life:"18-20 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Grazer/Browser",cs:"Least Concern"},
"bushbuck":{n:"Bushbuck",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Medium",cl:"Reddish Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Cape_bushbuck",d:"Shy, solitary antelope in thick bush and forest. Males have short spiralling horns and are darker than hornless females. Freeze when alarmed relying on camouflage. Can be surprisingly aggressive when cornered.",w:"25-80 kg",l:"1.1-1.5 m",life:"12-16 years",act:"Mostly nocturnal",diet:"Browser â€” leaves, herbs, fruit",cs:"Least Concern"},
"common-duiker":{n:"Common Duiker",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Small",cl:"Grey-Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Common_duiker",d:"The name 'duiker' comes from Afrikaans meaning 'diver', referring to their habit of diving into bush when startled. Small and solitary with a distinctive dark stripe down the face. Only males carry short, straight horns.",w:"12-25 kg",l:"80-115 cm",life:"8-11 years",act:"Nocturnal/Crepuscular",diet:"Browser â€” leaves, fruit, flowers",cs:"Least Concern"},
"cape-grysbok":{n:"Cape Grysbok",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Small",cl:"Reddish Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Cape_grysbok",d:"A small, stocky antelope endemic to the Western and Eastern Cape. Reddish-brown coat flecked with white hairs ('grys' is Afrikaans for grey). Strictly nocturnal and very shy. Only males have short horns.",w:"8-12 kg",l:"54-70 cm",life:"6-8 years",act:"Nocturnal",diet:"Browser â€” leaves, fruit",cs:"Least Concern"},
"steenbok":{n:"Steenbok",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Small",cl:"Reddish Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Steenbok",d:"One of the smallest and most elegant antelope, with large ears, large dark eyes, and a rufous coat. Only males carry short, upright horns. They bury their droppings â€” a behaviour unique among antelope.",w:"7-16 kg",l:"70-95 cm",life:"6-10 years",act:"Diurnal/Crepuscular",diet:"Browser/Grazer",cs:"Least Concern"},
"klipspringer":{n:"Klipspringer",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Small",cl:"Grey-Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Klipspringer",d:"The name means 'rock jumper' in Afrikaans. They walk on the tips of their hooves like tiny ballet dancers, giving superb grip on rocks. Their coarse, hollow hair provides insulation and cushioning. Found in the Zuurberg Mountains.",w:"8-18 kg",l:"75-115 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Browser â€” shrubs, herbs, fruit",cs:"Least Concern"},
"mountain-reedbuck":{n:"Mountain Reedbuck",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Medium",cl:"Grey-Brown",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Mountain_reedbuck",d:"A medium-sized antelope found on grassy mountain slopes in the Zuurberg section. Has a distinctive white bushy tail that it flashes when alarmed. Only males carry short, forward-curving horns. Often seen in small groups.",w:"22-37 kg",l:"1-1.3 m",life:"8-10 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Grazer â€” grasses",cs:"Endangered"},
"grey-rhebok":{n:"Grey Rhebok",c:"Mammal",s:"Antelope",sz:"Medium",cl:"Grey",i:"ğŸ¦Œ",wp:"Grey_rhebok",d:"A graceful antelope endemic to South Africa with woolly grey fur and a long, narrow face. Males have short, straight, upright horns. Found on mountain slopes and plateaus. Males are territorial and will chase intruders.",w:"18-30 kg",l:"1-1.2 m",life:"8-10 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Browser/Grazer",cs:"Near Threatened"},
