"bahama-pintail":{n:"Bahama Pintail",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Medium",cl:"Brown & White",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"White-cheeked_pintail",d:"An attractive dabbling duck with warm brown plumage, distinctive white cheeks, and a red bill base with blue tip. Native to the Caribbean, South America, and the Galapagos Islands. Often called the white-cheeked pintail. Feeds by upending in shallow water to reach aquatic vegetation.",w:"475-635 g",l:"38-48 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Omnivore â€” aquatic plants, seeds, invertebrates",cs:"Least Concern"},
"brazilian-teal":{n:"Brazilian Teal",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Small",cl:"Brown & Red",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Brazilian_teal",d:"A small, attractive duck native to South America. Males have a distinctive red bill, dark head with pale cheeks, and brown body with a bright iridescent green speculum bordered in white and black. Pairs bond strongly and are often seen together. Prefers shallow freshwater pools and marshes.",w:"340-415 g",l:"35-40 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Omnivore â€” seeds, aquatic plants, invertebrates",cs:"Least Concern"},
"canvasback":{n:"Canvasback",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Medium",cl:"Brown & White",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Canvasback",d:"North America's largest diving duck with a distinctive sloping forehead and long bill profile. Males have a rich chestnut-red head, black breast, and pale grey body that looks white at a distance. The name comes from the canvas-like appearance of the back plumage. A prized species among waterfowl enthusiasts.",w:"900-1,600 g",l:"48-56 cm",life:"10-16 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Omnivore â€” aquatic plants, tubers, invertebrates",cs:"Least Concern"},
"cape-shoveler":{n:"Cape Shoveler",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Medium",cl:"Brown",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Cape_shoveler",d:"A dabbling duck with warm brown plumage, a distinctively large spatulate bill, and a bright iridescent green speculum. Near-endemic to southern Africa. The oversized bill is used for filter-feeding by sweeping it through shallow water to strain tiny invertebrates and seeds from the surface.",w:"500-700 g",l:"44-53 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Omnivore â€” aquatic invertebrates, seeds, plants",cs:"Least Concern"},
"carolina-duck":{n:"Carolina Duck",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Medium",cl:"Multicoloured",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Wood_duck",d:"Also known as the wood duck, the male is arguably the most beautiful duck in North America with iridescent green and purple head, red eyes, ornate white markings, and chestnut breast. Nests in tree cavities, and day-old ducklings must leap from nest holes up to 15 metres high to reach the ground.",w:"450-680 g",l:"43-51 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Omnivore â€” seeds, nuts, aquatic plants, insects",cs:"Least Concern"},
"chestnut-teal":{n:"Chestnut Teal",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Small",cl:"Chestnut & Green",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Chestnut_teal",d:"A small, compact duck native to southern Australia. Males are striking with a glossy dark green head and rich chestnut body. Females are mottled brown. One of the few Australian ducks that tolerates saltwater, commonly found in coastal estuaries and mangroves as well as freshwater wetlands.",w:"550-800 g",l:"38-45 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Omnivore â€” seeds, aquatic plants, invertebrates",cs:"Least Concern"},
"chiloe-wigeon":{n:"Chiloe Wigeon",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Medium",cl:"Grey & Green",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Chilo%C3%A9_wigeon",d:"An attractive South American wigeon named after the Chiloe Island off Chile. Males have a distinctive metallic green head patch, grey barred body, and white forehead. Found in marshes, lakes, and coastal lagoons. Grazes on land more readily than most ducks, often feeding in flocks on short grass.",w:"700-1,000 g",l:"43-54 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” grasses, aquatic plants, seeds",cs:"Least Concern"},
"eurasian-wigeon":{n:"Eurasian Wigeon",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Medium",cl:"Brown & Cream",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Eurasian_wigeon",d:"A handsome dabbling duck with a round head and short bill. Breeding males have a chestnut head with a cream-yellow forehead, pink breast, and grey body. Native to Eurasia and a winter visitor to Africa. Often grazes on short grass near water, a behaviour less common in other ducks.",w:"500-1,000 g",l:"42-50 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” grasses, aquatic plants",cs:"Least Concern"},
"ferruginous-duck":{n:"Ferruginous Duck",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Medium",cl:"Rich Brown",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Ferruginous_duck",d:"A compact diving duck with rich, warm chestnut-brown plumage, bright white undertail coverts, and white eyes in males. Native to Eurasia and classified as Near Threatened due to wetland habitat loss. A shy duck that prefers densely vegetated freshwater pools and lakes.",w:"400-700 g",l:"38-42 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Omnivore â€” aquatic plants, seeds, invertebrates",cs:"Near Threatened"},
"fulvous-whistling-duck":{n:"Fulvous Whistling Duck",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Medium",cl:"Tawny",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Fulvous_whistling_duck",d:"A tall, long-necked duck with rich fulvous (tawny) plumage, a dark back with rufous-edged feathers, and distinctive white flank stripes. Found on four continents â€” the Americas, Africa, and Asia. Named for their high-pitched whistling call given in flight. Active mainly at night.",w:"600-900 g",l:"45-53 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Nocturnal/Crepuscular",diet:"Omnivore â€” seeds, aquatic plants, rice, invertebrates",cs:"Least Concern"},
"green-winged-teal":{n:"Green-winged Teal",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Small",cl:"Brown & Green",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Eurasian_teal",d:"One of the smallest dabbling ducks with a compact body and short neck. Males have a chestnut head with a sweeping green eye patch bordered in cream, grey vermiculated body, and a green speculum. Found across the Northern Hemisphere. Quick and agile in flight, often twisting and turning in tight flocks.",w:"250-400 g",l:"34-38 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Omnivore â€” seeds, aquatic plants, invertebrates",cs:"Least Concern"},
"laysan-teal":{n:"Laysan Teal",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Small",cl:"Brown",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Laysan_duck",d:"One of the world's rarest ducks, native only to a few small Hawaiian islands. Dark brown plumage with a distinctive white eye-ring and green-purple speculum. Once numbering as few as seven individuals in 1912, making them one of the greatest conservation recovery stories. Now carefully managed in captivity.",w:"370-500 g",l:"38-43 cm",life:"10-12 years",act:"Nocturnal/Crepuscular",diet:"Omnivore â€” invertebrates, seeds, algae",cs:"Critically Endangered"},
"mandarin-duck":{n:"Mandarin Duck",c:"Bird",s:"Duck",sz:"Small",cl:"Multicoloured",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Mandarin_duck",d:"Often considered the world's most beautiful duck. Males are extraordinarily ornate with a red bill, purple breast, orange 'sail' feathers on the back, and intricate patterns of green, white, and orange. Native to East Asia. In Chinese culture, mandarin ducks symbolise lifelong love and fidelity.",w:"428-693 g",l:"41-49 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Crepuscular",diet:"Omnivore â€” seeds, acorns, aquatic plants, insects",cs:"Least Concern"},
