"barnacle-goose":{n:"Barnacle Goose",c:"Bird",s:"Goose",sz:"Medium",cl:"Black & White",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Barnacle_goose",d:"A handsome goose with a distinctive white face, black head, neck, and breast, and grey-barred upperparts. Native to the Arctic regions of Europe. In medieval times, people believed they hatched from barnacles because no one had ever seen their nesting grounds in the remote Arctic.",w:"1.2-2.2 kg",l:"58-70 cm",life:"20-25 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” grasses, aquatic plants",cs:"Least Concern"},
"black-swan":{n:"Black Swan",c:"Bird",s:"Goose",sz:"Large",cl:"Black",i:"ğŸ¦¢",wp:"Black_swan",d:"An iconic Australian waterbird with entirely black plumage except for striking white flight feathers visible in flight, and a bright red bill. The discovery of black swans by Europeans in Australia overturned the centuries-old assumption that all swans were white, giving rise to the philosophical concept of the 'black swan event'.",w:"3.7-9 kg",l:"1.1-1.4 m",life:"20-40 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” aquatic plants, algae",cs:"Least Concern"},
"canada-goose":{n:"Canada Goose",c:"Bird",s:"Goose",sz:"Large",cl:"Brown & Black",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Canada_goose",d:"One of the most recognisable waterfowl with a black head and neck, white chinstrap, brown body, and pale breast. Native to North America where they are common and widespread. Mate for life and are devoted parents. Their V-formation flying and honking calls are iconic harbingers of seasonal change.",w:"2.6-6.5 kg",l:"75-110 cm",life:"10-24 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” grasses, grain, aquatic plants",cs:"Least Concern"},
"chinese-goose":{n:"Chinese Goose",c:"Bird",s:"Goose",sz:"Large",cl:"White or Brown",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Chinese_goose",d:"A domesticated form of the wild swan goose, characterised by a prominent knob at the base of the bill and an elongated, swan-like neck. One of the oldest domesticated goose breeds, kept for over 3,000 years in China. Excellent guard animals that raise a loud alarm at the approach of strangers.",w:"4-5 kg",l:"75-90 cm",life:"15-25 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” grasses, grain, aquatic plants",cs:"Least Concern"},
"common-shelduck":{n:"Common Shelduck",c:"Bird",s:"Goose",sz:"Medium",cl:"White & Green",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Common_shelduck",d:"A large, striking duck that bridges the gap between ducks and geese. Males and females are similar with a bold pattern of white, dark green head, chestnut breast band, and red bill â€” males with a prominent knob. Native to Eurasia. Nests in burrows and enclosed spaces, sometimes far from water.",w:"0.8-1.5 kg",l:"58-67 cm",life:"10-20 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Omnivore â€” molluscs, crustaceans, aquatic invertebrates",cs:"Least Concern"},
"maned-goose":{n:"Maned Goose",c:"Bird",s:"Goose",sz:"Medium",cl:"Grey & Brown",i:"ğŸ¦†",wp:"Australian_wood_duck",d:"Also known as the Australian wood duck, this distinctive species is more goose-like than duck-like with grey plumage, a dark brown head, and a short dark mane on the back of the neck. Males have a darker head and a speckled breast. Native to Australia. Grazes on land more than most waterfowl.",w:"0.7-1.1 kg",l:"44-50 cm",life:"10-15 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” grasses, clover, herbs",cs:"Least Concern"},
"mute-swan":{n:"Mute Swan",c:"Bird",s:"Goose",sz:"Very Large",cl:"White",i:"ğŸ¦¢",wp:"Mute_swan",d:"One of the heaviest flying birds in the world with elegant pure white plumage, a long S-curved neck, and an orange bill with a distinctive black knob. Native to Europe and Asia. Despite the name 'mute', they hiss, grunt, and snort. Their powerful wings can deliver blows strong enough to break a human arm when defending a nest.",w:"6.6-15 kg",l:"1.4-1.7 m",life:"20-30 years",act:"Diurnal",diet:"Herbivore â€” aquatic plants, grasses",cs:"Least Concern"},
